revision.text:
{{Aftermath of World War II in Yugoslavia}}
The '''Bleiburg repatriations''' ([[#Terminology|see terminology]]) occurred in May 1945, at the [[end of World War II in Europe]], when tens of thousands of soldiers and civilians associated with the [[Axis powers|Axis]] fleeing [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]] were [[Repatriation|repatriated]] to that country. They were subjected to forced marches together with captured columns in Yugoslavia. Tens of thousands were executed and many taken to forced labor camps. The events are named for the [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthian]] border town of [[Bleiburg]], where the initial repatriation was conducted.

On 3 May 1945, the government of the [[Independent State of Croatia]] (NDH), a [[fascist]] [[puppet state]] established in parts of [[Invasion of Yugoslavia|occupied Yugoslavia]], decided to flee to [[Ostmark (Austria)|Austria]] and have the remnants of the [[Croatian Armed Forces (Independent State of Croatia)|Croatian Armed Forces]] (HOS) move there as soon as possible in order to surrender to the [[British Army during the Second World War|British Army]]. The Axis-aligned Slovene leadership issued a retreat order for the [[Slovene Home Guard]] on the same day. These forces, accompanied by civilians, joined the German [[Army Group E]] and other Axis units in withdrawal, including the [[XV SS Cossack Cavalry Corps]] and the [[Montenegrin National Army]], that refused to surrender to the [[Red Army]] or the [[Yugoslav Partisans]].

In the week after the [[German Instrument of Surrender]], which marked the formal [[end of World War II in Europe]], Axis forces in Yugoslavia repeatedly refused to surrender and battled the Partisans to avoid encirclement and keep escape routes open. The Slovene-led columns fought their way to the Austrian border near [[Klagenfurt]] on 14 May. Their surrender was accepted by the British and were interned in the nearby Viktring camp. When one of the columns of fleeing HOS troops intermingled with civilians approached the town of Bleiburg on 15 May, the British refused to accept their surrender and directed them to surrender to the Partisans, which the HOS leadership did after short negotiations. Other Axis prisoners in British captivity were repatriated to Yugoslavia in the following weeks. The repatriations were canceled by the British on 31 May, following reports of massacres.

The Yugoslav authorities moved the prisoners on forced marches throughout the country to internment and labor camps. Mass executions were carried out, the largest of which were in [[Tezno massacre|Tezno]], [[Kočevski Rog massacre|Kočevski Rog]] and [[Barbara Pit massacre|Huda jama]]. The aftermath of the repatriations was a taboo topic in Yugoslavia and the public and official commemoration of the victims would only begin several decades after the events. The number of casualties that occurred at the time of the repatriations and in the weeks that followed has proven difficult to ascertain, with exact numbers being a subject of much debate.

==Terminology==
Commonly used terms such as ''Bleiburg massacre'', ''Bleiburg tragedy'', ''Bleiburg crime'', ''Bleiburg case'', and also simply ''Bleiburg'' are used in Croatia in reference to the events in question.<ref name="Dizdar"/><ref name="YatBT-1999"/><ref name="Grahek Ravančić">[[#Grahek Ravančić-2008|Grahek Ravančić, 2008]]</ref> 

The term ''Way of the Cross'' ({{lang-hr|Križni put}}) is a common subjective term, used mostly by Croatians, regarding the events after the repatriation itself.<ref name="Dizdar">[[#Dizdar-2005|Dizdar, 2005]]</ref> The latter have been described as "[[death march]]es".<ref name="Zerjavic"/>{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=765}}

==Background==
[[File:Corpses in the Sava river, Jasenovac camp, 1945.jpg|thumb|The [[Independent State of Croatia]] conducted a systematic campaign of mass murder of minorities. This May 1945 picture shows bodies thrown into the Sava River, near [[Sisak]].]]

When [[World War II]] broke out in 1939, the government of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] declared its neutrality,{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2008|p=8}} but most of its neighbours joined the [[Tripartite Pact]] by the beginning of 1941.{{sfn|Goldstein|1999|p=130}} Yugoslavia came under heavy pressure to join the [[Axis powers|Axis]] and the Yugoslav government signed the Pact on 25 March 1941. However, demonstrations broke out in [[Belgrade]] against the decision and on 27 March, the government was overthrown in a [[Yugoslav coup d'état|coup d'état]]. The new Yugoslav government refused to ratify the signing of the Tripartite Pact, though it did not rule it out. [[Adolf Hitler]] reacted by launching the [[invasion of Yugoslavia]] on 6 April 1941, together with [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] and [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920–46)|Hungary]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=46–47}}

On 10 April, German troops entered [[Zagreb]] and on the same day, the establishment of the [[Independent State of Croatia]] ({{lang-hr|Nezavisna Država Hrvatska}}, NDH) was declared, an Axis puppet state led by the [[Ustaše]]. [[Ante Pavelić]] was named the ''[[Poglavnik]]'' ("leader") of NDH.{{sfn|Tanner|2001|p=142}} Yugoslavia capitulated to the Axis powers on 17 April.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=53}} 

The rump Serbian territory was placed under [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia|German military administration]], with the help of a [[Government of National Salvation|civil puppet government]] led by [[Milan Nedić]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=63}} Slovene lands were divided between Germany, Italy and Hungary.{{sfn|Hančič|Podberšič|2008|p=44}}

Following the occupation and division of Yugoslavia, antisemitic laws were introduced in accordance to the Nazi [[Final Solution]] plan.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=583}} The Ustaše also enacted racial laws and systematically [[World War II persecution of Serbs|persecuted]] [[Serbs]], as well as [[History of the Jews in Croatia|Jewish]] and [[Romani people in Croatia|Roma]] populations throughout the country. A concentration camp system was established, the largest of which was [[Jasenovac concentration camp|Jasenovac]].{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=12}} A series of massacres led to armed revolts of Serbs against the NDH. Wehrmacht General [[Edmund Glaise-Horstenau]] blamed the Ustaše crimes for the uprisings and criticized the [[Government of the Independent State of Croatia|government of NDH]].{{sfn|Tanner|2001|p=157}}

In the wake of the invasion, remnants of the [[Royal Yugoslav Army]] organized the Serbian monarchist [[Chetniks]] as the first resistance movement. The Chetniks were led by [[Draža Mihailović]] and were recognized by the [[Yugoslav government-in-exile]].{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|pp=16–17}} The [[Communist Party of Yugoslavia]] refrained from open conflict with the Axis forces while the [[Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact]] between Germany and the Soviet Union was in effect. Following the start of [[Operation Barbarossa]], the Communist-led [[Yugoslav Partisans]] issued their call for an uprising.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|pp=9–10}} 

[[Josip Broz Tito]] was the supreme commander of the Partisan forces. The Chetniks and the Partisans, the two main guerrilla resistance units, initially cooperated against the Axis, but their cooperation soon fell apart and they turned against each other. The Chetniks started to collaborate with the Axis and Allied support shifted to the Partisan side.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=226}}{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=17}}

==End of the war==
[[File:1945-05-01GerWW2BattlefrontAtlas.jpg|thumb|Front lines in Europe on 1 May 1945]]
The arrival of Soviet ground troops in the [[Belgrade Offensive]] and Allied logistical support enabled the Partisans to increase their offensive actions. By the end of 1944, with the help of the [[Red Army]], they established control in Serbia, Macedonia, Montenegro and Dalmatia.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|pp=121-22}} German forces retreated from Serbia, together with Nedić's forces.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=228}} The Wehrmacht and the HOS established a [[Syrmian Front|front in Syrmia]] to secure the retreat of the German Army Group E from the Balkans.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=752}} [[Communist purges in Serbia in 1944–45|Mass killings]] of POWs and ethnic Germans followed after the Partisans secured control of Serbia.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=122}}

In May 1944, Tito founded an intelligence service known as the Department for People's Protection ([[OZNA]]), modeled after the Soviet [[NKVD]]. It represented a military intelligence service and a political secret police of the Communist Party.{{sfn|Mikola|2008|p=163}} In August 1944, he founded an army unit called People's Defence Force of Yugoslavia (''Korpus narodne odbrane Jugoslavije'', KNOJ), whose explicit assignment was to "liquidate Chetnik, Ustaša, White Guard and other anti-people gangs".{{sfn|Vuletić|2007|p=137}}

In August 1944, a coup d'état against Ante Pavelić, known as the [[Lorković–Vokić plot]], failed and its conspirators were arrested or executed. The main plotters wanted to align NDH with the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=425}} As the war progressed and it became clearer that the Axis would lose the war, the desertion rate in the NDH armed force grew, especially among the Croatian Home Guard.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=430}} The Chetniks also showed similar signs of desertion.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=17}} In contrast, the [[Ustaše Militia]] rarely disintegrated or defected to the Partisans.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=15}}

On 30 August 1944, Josip Broz Tito offered [[amnesty]] to Croatian Home Guards, [[Slovene Home Guard]]s and Chetniks if they chose to defect to the Partisan side by 15 September. After 15 September, all who had not defected were to be brought to "people's courts". Similar calls were repeated several times after the deadline. In some cases, Croatian Home Guards were killed despite defecting to the Partisans.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=121}}

The [[Croatian Armed Forces (Independent State of Croatia)|Armed Forces of the Independent State of Croatia]] (HOS) were reorganized in November 1944 to combine the units of the Ustaše and Croatian Home Guard.<ref>[[#Thomas-1995|Thomas, 1995]], p. 30</ref> Throughout the war, the treatment of prisoners from the Croatian Home Guard, was relatively benign {{spaced ndash}} Partisans would merely ridicule the captured ''domobran'' soldiers and then send them home if they didn't want to join the uprising. However, on 13 January 1945, Pavelić ordered the ''domobrani'' to merge with the [[Ustaša]] military, creating a force estimated at 280,000.{{sfn|Vuletić|2007|pp=136, 140}}

By 1945, the Yugoslav Partisans were known as the [[Yugoslav People's Army]], numbering more than 800,000 men organized into five [[field army|field armies]], and were in pursuit of the remnant of the defeated German and NDH forces.<ref>[[#Thomas-1995|Thomas, 1995]], p. 32</ref><ref>[[#Jancar-Webster-1989|Jancar-Webster, 1989]], p. 46</ref>

In March 1945, the 4th Yugoslav Army advanced through [[Lika]], [[Croatian Littoral]] and [[Kvarner Gulf]]. Most of Bosnia and Herzegovina was in Partisan hands by the end of April. On 12 April, the Syrmian Front was broken and the 1st and 3rd Army advanced west through Slavonia. Only the northwestern part of NDH with Zagreb as its center remained under control of NDH authorities.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=125}} There were a large number of refugees in that area from other parts of NDH. The Partisans carried out reprisals against captured soldiers of the HOS, as well as civilian political opponents.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|pp=127-28}}

==Axis retreat==
[[File:Umik Nemcev in domobrancev skozi Tržič.jpg|thumb|[[Slovene Home Guard]]s and Germans retreating through the town of [[Tržič]]]]
[[File:Slovenski begunci na cesti Tržič-Ljubelj.jpg|thumb|[[Slovene Home Guard]]s and civilians on the [[Tržič]]-[[Ljubelj]] road near [[Austria]]]]
[[File:Slovenski begunci na poti v Tržič.jpg|thumb|Slovene refugees heading to Austria]]
The collapse of the Syrmian front in April 1945 accelerated the withdrawal of German forces, that were in retreat from the Balkans since October 1944.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=752}} Like other Axis troops, forces of the NDH did not want to surrender to the Red Army or the Yugoslav Partisans and began retreating through Slovenia towards the Yugoslav-Austrian border, in order to surrender to the British forces advancing north from Italy.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=21}} A large-scale exodus of people was planned and organized by the authorities of the NDH despite the fact there was no strategic benefit to it: there simply was no viable destination for all the population to move to.{{sfn|Vuletić|2007|p=140}} On 3 May, the Slovene leadership also decided to retreat to Austria.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2010|p=864}}

Some in the NDH and Slovene political and military leadership believed that the Western Allies will use them as anti-Communist forces and thus enable them to return to Yugoslavia and restore power with their support. Slovenian Bishop [[Gregorij Rožman]] made an appeal to the Allies to occupy Slovenia and prevent the Communists from taking power.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=21}} The NDH leadership abolished racial laws and on 6 May sent a request for collaboration with the Allies,{{sfn|Radelić|2016|pp=9-10}} but all of these efforts failed.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=21}} While the NDH leadership may have organized a civilian retreat to bolster their claims that the Yugoslav Communists were after innocent civilian victims, the sheer number of civilians slowed down the retreat, made surrender to the Allies unfeasible, and ultimately led to the belief<!-- by whom? --> that they were nothing more than a [[human shield]] to the Ustaše.{{sfn|Vuletić|2007|p=140}} However, the majority of the civilian refugees consisted of those holding anti-Communist views or who feared reprisals.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=22}}

Divisions of three Yugoslav armies were pursuing Axis forces.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=752}} Some units of the Yugoslav 4th Army managed to reach Carinthia before or at the same time as the retreating columns. Additional divisions of the 3rd and 4th Army were sent to the area in order to capture southern Carinthia and stop the retreating columns. The 1st and the 2nd Army were halted near Celje, while the 3rd Army advanced further in pursuit of the retreating columns.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=23}}

On 6 May 1945, the collaborationist government of the NDH fled [[Zagreb]], and arrived to a location near [[Klagenfurt]], Austria on 7 May.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=132}} Pavelić and the military leadership left [[Zaprešić]] on the evening of 7 May, intending to join the rest of his regime in Austria.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=133}} The bulk of the NDH leadership, including Pavelić, escaped in early May, fleeing to Western Europe and Latin America; Partisans were therefore only able to capture a small number of senior military NDH officers.{{sfn|Vuletić|2007|p=141}}

Zagreb was defended by parts of the 1st Division of the Army of NDH and the [[41st Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|41st]] and [[181st Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|181st German Divisions]], deployed along the unfinished fortified "Zvonimir line" between [[Sveti Ivan Žabno]] and [[Ivanić-Grad]]. The fierce battle with the Yugoslav 1st Army lasted from 5-8 May. The 7 May was the single bloodiest day in the 1,240-day long history of the [[1st Proletarian Brigade]], with 158 killed and 358 wounded in the fighting for [[Vrbovec]].{{sfn|Miladinović|1991|p=1187}}

Besides the HOS, the Slovene Home Guard and the German [[Army Group E]], there were also other military formations that were retreating.{{sfn|Portmann|2004|p=68}} The remnants of the [[Serbian State Guard]], two regiments of the [[Serbian Volunteer Corps (World War II)|Serbian Volunteer Corps]] and a group of Chetniks surrendered to the British near the Italian-Yugoslav border on 5 May. These units were not repatriated to Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2008|p=265}} The [[Montenegrin National Army]], formed in April 1945 by [[Sekula Drljević]] with the support of the NDH government, to gather Montenegrins from NDH in the unit, were retreating together with Croatian forces.{{sfn|Grahek Ravančić|2009|p=45}} Thousands of Russian Cossacks of the [[XVth SS Cossack Cavalry Corps]], stationed in Yugoslavia since 1943, were also retreating to Austria.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=134}} 

Tolstoy quotes a General Alexander telegram, sent to the Combined Chiefs of Staff, noting "50,000 Cossacks including 11,000 women, children and old men".<ref name="Tolstoy-1986"/> Shortly after midnight on 13 May 1945 the [[V Corps (United Kingdom)|British V Corps]] Headquarters in Austria estimated that there were "approximately 30,000 POWs, surrendered personnel, and refugees in the Corps area. A further 60,000 reported moving north to Austria from Yugoslavia".<ref>{{cite book|title=Southeastern Europe, 1918–1995|publisher=Croatian Heritage Foundation & Croatian Information Centre|year=2000|isbn=953-6525-05-4|chapter=The Bleiburg Massacres|first=Nikolai|last=Tolstoy}}</ref>{{dubious|date=January 2012}}

On 7 May 1945, Germany surrendered unconditionally to the Allied powers, marking the practical [[end of World War II in Europe]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=755}} The [[German Instrument of Surrender]] applied to German [[Wehrmacht]] forces in Yugoslavia as well as those armed forces under German command such as the Croatian Armed Forces. This would ordinarily have meant that they too had to cease their activities on 8 May and stay where they found themselves. The Ustaše military, however, came under the command of Pavelić,{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=754-55}} because as they were about to surrender, General [[Alexander Löhr]], Commander-in-Chief of [[Army Group E]] handed command of the Croatian forces to Pavelić on 8 May.{{sfn|Vuletić|2007|p=141}} Pavelić issued an order from [[Rogaška Slatina]] for his troops not to surrender to the Partisans, but to escape to Austria, to implement the Croatian government's decision of 3 May to flee to Austria.{{sfn|Vuletić|2007|p=141}} Following the capitulation of Germany on 8 May, Tito issued an address via [[Radio Belgrade]] on 9 May calling upon all armed collaborators to surrender, threatening "merciless response" from the people and the army should they refuse to do so.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|pp=134-35}}

On 8 May, Zagreb was liberated by the Partisan 1st and 2nd Army, with relatively few skirmishes and casualties in the city itself: the 1st Army reported to the General Staff that 10,901 enemy soldiers had been killed and 15,892 captured in taking Zagreb.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=134}} That same day, the headquarters of the 51st Vojvodina Division of the Yugoslav 3rd Army issued a dispatch ordering its units to consider all enemy officers and soldiers who continue resistance after midnight that day, and who are not part of units who had an organized surrender, as persons who do not have the status of [[prisoners of war]], and to treat them as bandits. The German surrender obstructed the progress of the columns fleeing Croatia northward. By 9 May, Partisan forces had moved into [[Maribor]] which eliminated that escape route. They also took control of [[Celje]] on 10 May, but with a force insufficient to halt the columns that were escaping towards [[Dravograd]].{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|pp=134-35}}

===Escape route to Klagenfurt-Viktring===
The Slovene Home Guard and Slovene civilians primarily used the route across the [[Loibl Pass]].{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=21}} Around 30,000 soldiers, including 10,000 to 12,000 Slovene Home Guards, 10,000 Germans, 4,000 Serbs, 4,000 members of the [[Russian Corps]], and 6,000 Slovene civilians, were withdrawing to Austria.{{sfn|Portmann|2004|p=71}} The road to Loibl (''Ljubelj'') was congested with loaded cars, trucks, wagons and horse carts. Battles with the Partisans also slowed down the retreat.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=23}} 

After passing the Loibl Pass, the columns were headed to the Drava Bridge at Hollenburg. The British were located north of the bridge. The bridge was guarded by German soldiers and was attacked by the Partisans on 7 May. Partisan reinforcements arrived on the following day and they set a barrier between [[Ferlach]] and Hollenburg, while units of the 4th Motorized Division and the 26th Division of the 4th Army were approaching Ferlach from the west. The Axis troops and civilians were surrounded and tried to fight their way through the blockades, but some German troops surrendered to the Partisans in the Rosental Valley.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|pp=25-26}} 

On 10 May, the main breakthrough attempt took place. The assault was carried out by the Slovene Home Guard, led by Vuk Rupnik, and the 7th SS Division "Prinz Eugen" and SS police units.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|pp=28-29}} A radio contact was established with the British who were ready to accept them if they managed to cross the Drava. The British did not attack the Axis units fighting the Partisans. The Home Guard and SS troops launched an infantry attack on the town of Ferlach and took control of it on the evening. The remaining Partisan units in the vicinity were repelled on 11 May and the column of troops and refugees began crossing the Drava River. They were taken by the British to the Viktring camp near [[Klagenfurt]]. By 14 May, all units of the Slovene Home Guard surrendered to the British.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|pp=31-33}}

===Escape route to Bleiburg===
[[File:Begunci na poti na Koroško.jpg|thumb|A column of refugees near the city of [[Celje]]]]
Croat troops and civilians mostly used escape routes towards [[Mežica]] and Bleiburg, and across the [[Kamnik–Savinja Alps|Kamnik Alps]] towards the Juan Valley in Austria.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=21}} The main Croatian column moved through the towns of Zidani Most, Celje, Štošanj, and Slovenj Gradec. On 11 May, the vanguard of the column reached Dravograd. However, the bridges across the Drava River were barricaded by Bulgarian units that reached the area on 9 May.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=34}} On 11–12 May, generals [[Vjekoslav Servatzy]] and [[Vladimir Metikoš]] entered discussions with [[First Army (Bulgaria)#World War II for the Allies|Bulgarian generals]] to allow the Croatian column to pass into Austria.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=136}} The discussions were inconclusive, but the Bulgarians suggested they head in the direction of [[Prevalje]] and Bleiburg, which the column did.<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-547">[[#Grahek Ravančić-2008|Grahek Ravančić, 2008]], p. 547</ref> Bleiburg was located some four kilometres northwest of the border of Austria and Yugoslavia. Parts of the columns that had weak or no protection were attacked by the Partisans - on 12 May, ''[[Politika]]'' carried Yugoslav Army reports of 15,700 prisoners of war in [[Maribor]], [[Zidani Most]], [[Bled, Slovenia|Bled]], [[Jesenice, Jesenice|Jesenice]] and elsewhere. On 13 May, they reported over 40,000 prisoners taken near [[Rogaška Slatina]], [[Celje]], [[Velenje]], [[Šoštanj]], [[Dravograd]], and elsewhere.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|pp=135-36}}

The main column was encircled in the Dravograd pocket. The Croatian Armed Forces had artillery positions in a five kilometers linear distance from Dravograd to the south and used howitzers to fire on positions of the Yugoslav Army. On the night of 13 May, the elite HOS infantry units, commanded by General [[Rafael Boban]], managed to break through the Partisan blockade and the column moved west through [[Ravne na Koroškem]] and [[Poljana, Prevalje|Poljana]] towards Bleiburg.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|pp=34-35}}{{sfn|Grahek Ravančić|2009|pp=85-86}} A large number of Croat soldiers and civilians reached the field at Bleiburg on 14 May.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=137}} The [[38th (Irish) Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|38th (Irish) Infantry Brigade]] headquarters were set up in Bleiburg,{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=143}} having occupied the town on 12 May,{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=137}} while the rest of the [[V Corps (United Kingdom)|V Corps]] was stationed in [[Klagenfurt]].{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=143}} By 14 May, the British accepted thousands of retreating troops and civilians.{{sfn|Ferenc|2008|p=155}}

==Surrender at Bleiburg==
[[File:Kolona Ustašev in hrvaških beguncev blizu Pliberka.jpg|thumb|The retreating column of the [[Croatian Armed Forces (Independent State of Croatia)|Croatian Armed Forces]] approaching the town of [[Bleiburg]] in May 1945]]
The main group of HOS troops and Croat civilians reached the Bleiburg field on 15 May. They were the head of the 45-65 kilometres long columns, numbering around 25,000 to 30,000 people.{{sfn|Lowe|2012|p=253}}{{sfn|Portmann|2004|p=68}} The group included various branches of the NDH army, including the [[Air Force of the Independent State of Croatia|Air Force]], Croatian Home Guard and Ustaše Militia, and civilian refugees. Most of them camped near the local railroad embankment. The Montenegrin National Army was placed east of the embankment.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=37}} Around 175,000 people were still on Yugoslav territory and moving towards Bleiburg.{{sfn|Lowe|2012|p=253}} Negotiations between representatives of the HOS, the Yugoslav Army and the British were held on the same day in the Bleiburg Castle.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=38}} The British negotiator was Brigadier [[Thomas Scott (British Army officer)|Thomas Scott]] of the 38th (Irish) Infantry Brigade.<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-535">[[#Grahek Ravančić-2008|Grahek Ravančić (2008)]], p. 535</ref> Ustaša infantry general [[Ivo Herenčić]] of the V Ustaša Corps, and a translator, Colonel Danijel Crljen, were involved in the surrender negotiations.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=758}}<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-544">[[#Grahek Ravančić-2008|Grahek Ravančić (2008)]], p. 544</ref>

In the afternoon of the same day, the Croatian forces started raising white flags in surrender.<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-543">[[#Grahek Ravančić-2008|Grahek Ravančić (2008)]], p. 543</ref> The Partisan representatives included Major-General Milan Basta, the political commissar of the 51st Vojvodina Division, and Lieutenant Colonel Ivan Kovačič Efenka of the 14th Attack Division.<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-547"/>{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=758}} NDH military representatives attempted to negotiate a surrender to the British, but were directed to surrender to the Yugoslav military.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=758}} The Independent State of Croatia had joined the [[Geneva Convention]] on 20 January 1943, and was recognised by it as a "belligerent".<ref name="Shaw, 1973, p.101">[[#Shaw-1973|Shaw, 1973]], p. 101</ref>

The Partisan forces of the 51st Vojvodina Brigade of the Yugoslav 3rd Army and the 14th Slovenian Division had established tactical control over the field of Bleiburg.{{sfn|Dizdar|2005|p=143}} Milan Basta set an ultimatum to the NDH negotiators - unconditional surrender within one hour, or else they would attack them and not uphold the norms of the international conventions of the Red Cross.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=758}}{{sfn|Vuletić|2007|p=135}} Basta's ultimatum was extended for another fifteen minutes, after which point a general surrender started.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=758}}
[[File:Zajeti ustaši na avstrijsko-slovenski meji.jpg|thumb|left|[[Independent State of Croatia|NDH]] [[POW]]s at Bleiburg on 15 May 1945, after the surrender]]
The exact events after the expiry of the ultimatum are the source of the original controversy regarding the repatriations. Teodor Pavić, described as a NDH "courier", wrote that the Partisan forces began strafing the crowd in the Bleiburg field with machine guns and shooting them individually.{{sfn|Vuletić|2007|p=135}} Petar Brajović, a Yugoslav officer, described a fifteen- to twenty-minute machine gun and mortar fire on the column.<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-545"/> Strle wrote that the 3rd Battalion of the 11th "Zidanšek" Brigade and the 3rd Battalion of the 1st "Tomšič" Brigade were involved in the fire, and their records noted at least 16 deaths, mainly from the machine gun fire.<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-545"/> A Croatian soldier who survived, Zvonimir Zorić, wrote of a massacre at Bleiburg.<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-545">[[#Grahek Ravančić-2008|Grahek Ravančić, 2008]], p. 545</ref>
[[File:Schematische Darstellung (Dr. Rulitz) Das Massaker auf dem Bleiburger Feld durch die Staatsgrenze zwischen Österreich und Jugoslawien (Slowenien) getrennt.jpg|thumb|Schematic representation of the situation on the Bleiburger field in May 1945]]
The notion of a massacre at the Bleiburg field was promoted by the remnants of the Ustaša in exile.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=757}} Croatian-American historian [[Jozo Tomasevich]] notes that it would have been physically impossible to assemble all the Croatian refugees in Bleiburg itself, so German and Croatian troops who are said to have surrendered "in Bleiburg" must have done so in various localities, including Bleiburg, and certainly not all in Bleiburg itself. He considers it impossible to establish the exact number of troops and civilians who tried to flee to Austria and were forced to surrender to the Partisans, and stresses that the number of victims has been inflated by pro-[[Ustaša]] sources for propaganda purposes, while communist sources have been diminishing it for similar reasons.<ref>[[#Tomasevich_2001|Tomasevich, 2001]], pp. 763-64</ref> Croatian historian Martina Grahek Ravančić<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vjesnik.hr/Article.aspx?ID=1C2FC45F-5591-42C1-8388-C79901D94A93|language=Croatian|newspaper=[[Vjesnik]]|title=Počelo suočavanje s negativnim naslijeđem antifašizma|date=12 February 2011}}{{deadlink|date=November 2016}}</ref> wrote that the complete extent of the casualties sustained by the NDH column at Bleiburg on the day of the surrender was not described in any available sources. She described a short Yugoslav Army attack on the column as a certainty, likewise that there were casualties, but the number is unknown.<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-546">[[#Grahek Ravančić-2008|Grahek Ravančić, 2008]], p. 546</ref>

Strle and Milan Basta claimed that as Ustaša forces tried to make a breakthrough at the north side of the valley, three British tanks were engaged to stop them, reportedly resulting in numerous casualties as well. However, only three Croatians provided testimony which supported the notion that there were British tanks in the proximity of the column, but with no mention of such a grave incident.<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-545"/> These kinds of unconfirmed reports of British military involvement, coupled with the actually legitimate acts of repatriation, were subsequently exaggerated by Ustaša supporters, particularly in the Croatian diaspora, in biased published works to accuse the British of war crimes.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=757}}

Later the same day, NDH generals [[Slavko Štancer]], [[Vjekoslav Servatzy]] and [[Vladimir Metikoš]] oversaw the surrender to the Partisans.<ref name="Grahek Ravančić-546"/> British army reports say Štancer had previously been captured by the Partisans when they strayed from the column, seeking the British.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=758}} The surrender continued for several days and at various locations; it took until 21 May for Tito to order the Partisans to withdraw from [[Carinthia]].<ref>[[#Ramet-2006|Ramet, 2006]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=FTw3lEqi2-oC&pg=PA159 p. 159].</ref>

