==Coverage and aftermath==
The events in the aftermath of the war were censored in Yugoslavia. Mass graves were concealed or destroyed, in accordance with an order by the Federal Ministry of Domestic Affairs from 18 May 1945.{{sfn|Ferenc|2008|p=157}} Relatives of the victims faced persecution and were treated as second class groups.{{sfn|Dežman|2008|p=201}} Until the 1950s, there were strict border controls in Yugoslavia, but tens of thousands of people emigrated illegally.{{sfn|Hančič|Podberšič|2008|p=55}}

It was not possible to visit the graves located in Yugoslavia, so Bleiburg in Austria became the main location where political emigrants, survivors or families of the victims could gather and hold a commemoration.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|pp=137-138}} The first Croats to return to the fields of Bleiburg to commemorate the victims came in 1952 on [[All Saints' Day]]. Since then, the Bleiburg Honorary Guard (''Počasni bleiburški vod''), an association founded by Croatian emigrants, organized an annual commemorative event, together with the Catholic Church in Carinthia. The Yugoslav consulate in Klagenfurt sent diplomatic protests to the Austrian government, but the commemorations were never banned by Austria.{{sfn|Pavlaković|2010|p=134}}{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=137}} The commemoration was seen as a provocation by Yugoslavia. Prohibited [[National symbols of Croatia|Croatian symbols]] were openly displayed and it drew attention to postwar killings which the Yugoslav authorities denied.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=175}} The Bleiburg events were also used as a tool for [[historical revisionism]] and the focus of collective resentment by the remainder of the Ustaše and their supporters. The number of victims was artificially inflated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/slavko-goldstein--nisu-svi-zlocini-uvijek-isti---pa-tako-nisu-isti-ni-bleiburg-i-jasenovac/985222|language=Croatian|title=Nisu svi zločini uvijek isti&nbsp;... pa tako nisu isti ni Bleiburg i Jasenovac|first=Slavko|last=Goldstein|authorlink=Slavko Goldstein|newspaper=Jutarnji list|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref>

[[File:Schematische Darstellung (Dr. Rulitz) Lokalisationen der Massaker von Bleiburg im österreichischen Kärnten und Slowenien.jpg|thumb| Places in Austria and Slovenia, one of the May and June 1945 mass killings]]

The Yugoslav [[State Security Administration]] (UDBA) monitored the activities of the participants of the commemorative event and conducted a series of attacks on its organizers. During the ceremony in 1966, a bomb exploded in a country inn in Loibach, but none of the attendants was injured. Nikica Martinović, the chairman of the Bleiburg Honorary Guard, was assassinated by the UDBA in Klagenfurt in 1975. The following year a bomb was found in front of the tavern of Mirko Karačić, also a member of the Bleiburg Honorary Guard. In spite of the threats and attacks, the commemoration continued to be held annually until the [[breakup of Yugoslavia]].{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|pp=138-140}}

Gatherings and commemorations were also held in other countries. In 1960, on the 15th anniversary commemoration held in [[Cleveland]], the Bleiburg Tragedy Research Committee was founded by Croatian emigrants.{{sfn|Grahek Ravančić|2009|p=13}} In 1961, the commemoration in Cleveland was attended by US Congressman [[Michael A. Feighan]]. The Yugoslav consul in [[Pittsburgh]], Ivan Mirošević, protested against it and requested the gathering to be banned. Feighan criticized the consul and Josip Broz Tito during his speech at the commemoration. Mirošević was expelled from the US for his comments.{{sfn|Prcela|Živić|2001|pp=XXIV-XXV}} In 1965, commemorating the 20th anniversary, US Senator [[Frank Lausche]] condemned the post-war killings in Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Prcela|Živić|2001|pp=91-92}} Organizations of Croatian emigrants in Germany and USA requested a Red Cross investigation of mass grave sites, but Yugoslavia rejected it.{{sfn|Prcela|Živić|2001|pp=104-105}}

In 1976, a marble monument was erected in the Unter-Loibach cemetery and in 1987, a monument was erected on the Bleiburg field with the inscription "In Honor and Glory of the Fallen Croatian Army, May 1945" in Croatian and German language. The monument had the Croatian [[Coat of arms of Croatia|coat of arms]] and the Islamic [[star and crescent]] engraved.{{sfn|Pavlaković|2010|p=134}}

==Investigations of mass graves==
[[File:Notranjost Barbara rova.jpg|thumb|Interior of the Barbara Pit near [[Huda Jama]], [[Slovenia]], reached in March 2009]]
Discussions about the post-war massacres were forbidden in Yugoslavia, so the investigations of mass grave locations began only in the 1990s, after the fall of communism.{{sfn|Ferenc|2008|pp=157-158}} In 1992, 1163 bodies were excavated from 23 [[Macelj massacre|mass graves in the forests of Macelj]], leaving around 130 possible mass grave locations unexplored.<ref name="vecernji-2012">{{cite news|url=http://www.vecernji.hr/regije/macelj-gora-zlocina-clanak-410508|newspaper=[[Večernji list]]|language=Croatian|title=Macelj - gora zločina!|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> In 2002, the Slovenian government established the Governmental Committee for Settlement of Questions on Secret Mass Graves, with the assignment of "recording of data about the number and locations of mass graves" after the end of World War II.{{sfn|Ferenc|2008|pp=157-158}}

The Tezno mass graves near Maribor were discovered in 1999 during the construction of a motorway. There were 1,179 corpses in the excavated strip. In 2007, the [[Commission on Concealed Mass Graves in Slovenia]], founded in 2005, analyzed the Tezno trench and found human remains at a length of 740 metres, estimated to contain the remains of around 15,000 victims.{{sfn|Ferenc|2012|p=568}} In 2009, the [[Barbara Pit]] was uncovered in Slovenia, holding 726 human remains.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/77937/Default.aspx|language=Croatian|title=Stratišta: "U iskapanju Hude jame Hrvati nam moraju pomoći, tamo su oni ubijali svoje"|newspaper=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> The same year, more pits were uncovered on two locations near the Croatian-Slovenian border, one near the village of [[Harmica]] and the other near [[Gornji Hrašćan]], estimated to hold, together, around 4,500 bodies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/jos-jedna-masovna-grobnica-otkrivena-uz-hrvatskoslovensku-granicu-koliko-ih-jos-ima/428304.aspx|language=Croatian|publisher=Index.hr|title=Još jedna masovna grobnica otkrivena uz hrvatsko-slovensku granicu: Koliko ih još ima?|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>

By mid 2008, 581 concealed grave sites were registered by the Slovenian Commission on Concealed Mass Graves. The number rose to more than 600 grave sites in 2010. The commission estimates that there are around 100,000 victims in those graves in Slovenia alone.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=109}} Unlike in Slovenia, there was no serious research of mass graves in Croatia by the Croatian government.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=112}} In 1991, the Croatian Parliament established the Commission for Determination of War and Post-war Victims. The Commission began its work in 1994, but was abolished in 2002, with no significant contribution to the research.{{sfn|Grahek Ravančić|2009|p=23}}

==Number of victims==
The modern-day consensus is that the number of deaths of the forced marches and in death camps rose to tens of thousands, and included civilians.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/143561/Croatia/223956/World-War-II|title=History of Croatia, World War II|authors=C.W. Bracewell, John R. Lampe|work=Encyclopædia Britannica Online|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica Inc.|year=2012|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> The number of casualties, provided by the literature dealing with the Bleiburg repatriations and its aftermath, mostly ranges from about 50,000 to 200,000-250,000. Based on statistical calculations, a minimum of 70,000 to 80,000 people were killed.{{sfn|Geiger|2013|p=94}} However, the exact number of those who met their death after the end of the war is impossible to ascertain accurately.{{sfn|Grahek Ravančić|2009|p=330}} Generally, there are three approaches to the number of victims:

The historiographic investigations of scientists include:
* Croatian-American historian [[Jozo Tomasevich]] uses Žerjavić's estimates in his 2001 book and accepts the number of 70,000 killed in the events connected with Bleiburg and Viktring, including around 50,000 Croats and [[Bosniaks]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=765}}
* In April 2008, the Slovenian Presidency of the [[Council of the European Union]] organized the [[European Public Hearing on Crimes Committed by Totalitarian Regimes]], and the resulting document included various research including that of [[Mitja Ferenc]], noting official data on 3,986 known wartime graves and [[mass graves in Slovenia]] from World War II,{{sfn|Ferenc|2008|p=155}} Milko Mikola, indicating that the victims were executed en masse without a trial,{{sfn|Mikola|2008|p=145}} and [[Jerca Vodušek Starič]] who wrote about purported mass killings following liberation of Slovenia and Croatia in May 1945: "It is impossible to find out the exact number of those liquidated. Today the number reaches 14,531 Slovenes and an estimate [of] 65,000 to 100,000 Croats (mainly the Croat Home-guard, which was the regular army and not ustasha forces). Among them were also civilians."<ref>[[#EPHCCTR-2008|European Public Hearing on "Crimes Committed by Totalitarian Regimes", 2008]], Jerca<!-- misspelled Jera in the book itself --> Vodušek Starič: p. 36.</ref>
* In 2011, Ferenc, in charge of uncovering post-war graves in Slovenia, publicly estimated the total number of all the killed in "the tens of thousands", certainly less than 100,000. He also stated that of the Slovene victims, 93% were soldiers, collaborators with Nazi occupying forces.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/zgodbe/sobotnapriloga/mitja-ferenc-sprave-ne-bo-nadomestil-domovinski-spomenik-sredi-ljubljane.html|date=6 November 2011|newspaper=[[Delo]]|title=Mitja Ferenc: Sprave ne bo nadomestil domovinski spomenik sredi Ljubljane|language=Slovenian|accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref>
* Croatian historian [[Ivo Goldstein]], in the chapter ''Raspad i slom NDH, Bleiburg i križni put'' of his book ''Hrvatska 1918. - 2008.'' (''Croatia 1918-2008''), has posited that contemporary documentation supports the existence of up to 116,000 NDH soldiers and up to 60,000 Croatian civilians in the main columns through Slovenia. In addition, on a separate route there were around 17,000 members of the Slovene Home Guard, the [[Serbian Volunteer Corps (World War II)|Serbian Volunteer Corps]], Chetniks and some smaller NDH army units, together with around 10,000 Slovenian civilians. No precise assessment is made about the number of victims out of those totals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/raspad-i-slom-ndh--bleiburg-i-krizni-put/266118 |title=Raspad i slom NDH, Bleiburg i križni put |first=Ivo |last=Goldstein |authorlink=Ivo Goldstein |newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]] |date=8 November 2008 |accessdate=28 May 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107003522/http://www.jutarnji.hr/raspad-i-slom-ndh--bleiburg-i-krizni-put/266118/ |archivedate=7 November 2012 |df= }}</ref>
* British political scientist [[David B. MacDonald]] wrote a comprehensive root cause analysis of the inflated numbers in his 2003 book:<ref name="MacDonald pp. 170-171"/><blockquote>By contrast with Jasenovac, however, most impartial historians converged on much lower number of dead, suggesting that Bleiburg was by no means as significant as the largest death-camp in Yugoslavia.&nbsp;... [[Jasper Ridley]] attempts a more precise figure, although there is no way of knowing for sure.&nbsp;... Of these, he noted that the Allies agreed to surrender 23,000 to the Partisans between 24 and 29 May - a mixture of Slovenians, Serbians, and Croatians. Reports from the time according to Ridley,<ref>[[#Ridley-1994|Ridley, 1994]].</ref> indicate that not all 23,000 were killed.</blockquote>

Estimates have also been based on [[archeological]] evidence from [[mass grave]]s found in Slovenia. There were 581 grave sites being investigated by the [[Commission on Concealed Mass Graves in Slovenia|Slovenian Commission on Concealed Mass Graves]], {{as of|2009|October|lc=on}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/u-581-grobnici-je-100-000-zrtava/310887 |newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]]|language=Croatian|title=U 581 Grobnici je 100.000 žrtava|date=1 October 2009|accessdate=6 July 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806050043/http://www.jutarnji.hr/u-581-grobnici-je-100-000-zrtava/310887|archivedate=6 August 2012}}</ref>

Various authors base their claims on demographic calculations, accumulated eyewitness accounts, etc.:
* Croatian demographer [[Vladimir Žerjavić]], in 1992, estimated that around 70,000 people were killed at Bleiburg and during the death marches in 1945, including between 45,000 and 55,000 Croats and [[Bosniaks]], 8,000 to 10,000 Slovenes and around 2,000 Serbs and Montenegrins.{{sfn|Geiger|2013|p=94}}<ref name="Zerjavic">Vladimir Žerjavić, [http://www.hic.hr/books/manipulations/p07.htm Yugoslavia, Manipulations with the Number of Second World War Victims], hic.hr; accessed 18 September 2015.</ref>{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=765}}
* British journalist [[Misha Glenny]] wrote in his 1999 book, ''The Balkans: Nationalism, War and the Great Powers, 1804–1999'', "As German troops streamed out of Yugoslavia the Croat fascist leader Ante Pavelić and 100-200,000 Ustaša troops and civilians set off for the Austrian border on 7 May 1945, with Partisan forces in hot pursuit. They got as far as Bleiburg, a small Austrian border town, before being surrounded by British troops to the north and Partisans to the south. With RAF [[Spitfire]]s buzzing overhead, about 30-40,000 soldiers, including Pavelić, managed to disappear into the surrounding woods and then deep into Austria. But the remainder were taken prisoner by Partisan forces amid scenes of carnage. Some 30,000 Ustaše were killed on the four-day march towards the Slovene town of Maribor. On 20 May, in the [[Tezno trench]], 50,000 Croat soldiers and about 30,000 refugees, mainly women and children, were executed over a five-day period."<ref>[[#Glenny-1999|Glenny, 1999]], p. 530</ref>
* Former Yugoslav diplomat Cvijeto Job, wrote in his 2002 book, ''Yugoslavia's Ruin: The Bloody Lessons of Nationalism, a Patriot's Warning'', that during the 1990s, reports in the independent press in Croatia {{Clarify|date=May 2015}} cited the actual figures of killed at Bleiburg at between 12,000 and 15,000.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yH3Hz2AXonwC&pg=PA28|author=Job, Cvijeto|title=Yugoslavia's Ruin: The Bloody Lessons of Nationalism, a Patriot's Warning|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2002|isbn=0-7425-1784-5|page=28|accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref>
*In 2007, the association of Croatian Partisans published ''Bleiburg i Križni put 1945'' (''Bleiburg and the Way of the Cross 1945''), edited by Juraj Hrženjak,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://novine.novilist.hr/default.asp?WCI=Rubrike&WCU=285A285B2863285E2863285A28582858285F286328982897288F28632863285A285F285F285A2861285D2863286328632863O|language=Croatian|newspaper=[[Novi list]]|author=Pilsel, Drago|title=Antifašisti priznaju partizanske zločine|accessdate=7 February 2013}}<!--ISSN/ISBN needed, if any--></ref> which claimed the majority of victims at Bleiburg were killed by various means at the hands of Ustaše execution squads from elite formations such as the [[Crna Legija]] (''Black Legion''), which treated all soldiers attempting to surrender as traitors and deserters. According to this research, a figure of between 12,000 and 14,000 people were shot after returning to Yugoslavia. Additionally, 20 individuals committed suicide {{citation needed|date=September 2015}} and at least 1,500 concentration camp guards were shot near [[Maribor]]. {{citation needed|date=May 2012}}

==Legacy==
===Commemoration===
[[File:Tezno commemoration 2015.jpg|thumb|[[Josip Leko]], then-[[Speaker of the Croatian Parliament]], lays a wreath at the [[Tezno mass graves|Tezno Memorial]] in May 2015]]
With the transition to democracy in the 1980s and 1990s, the interest in revealing information about the Bleiburg repatriations grew, and it continued to be abused for revisionist purposes in the Croatian mainstream.<ref name="Butković-2009">{{cite news|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/kraj-ustaske-ikonografije/282644 |language=Croatian |title=Kraj ustaške ikonografije |first=Davor |last=Butković |newspaper=Jutarnji list |date=10 January 2009 |accessdate=29 May 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107003630/http://www.jutarnji.hr/kraj-ustaske-ikonografije/282644/ |archivedate=7 November 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref name="Pauković-2012">{{cite web|url=http://www.cpi.hr/hr-14096_povijest_malo_sadasnjosti_pa_opet_povijest.htm|language=Croatian|title=Povijest, malo sadašnjosti, pa opet povijest|first=Davor|last=Pauković|year=2012|publisher=The Political Science Research Centre|location=Zagreb|accessdate=24 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402123156/http://www.cpi.hr/hr-14096_povijest_malo_sadasnjosti_pa_opet_povijest.htm#|archive-date=2015-04-02|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
In May 1994, an International Symposium for Investigation of the Bleiburg Tragedy was held in both Zagreb and Bleiburg, where several authors discussed the deaths at Bleiburg and estimated them to be in the tens of thousands. This was later published by [[Školska knjiga]] as ''Od Bleiburga do naših dana''.<!--English language translation, please--><ref name="YatBT-1999">{{cite web|url=http://www.ess.uwe.ac.uk/genocide/yugoslav-hist1.htm |first=C. Michael |last=McAdams |title=Yalta and The Bleiburg Tragedy |year=1999 |accessdate=24 March 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816025402/http://www.ess.uwe.ac.uk/genocide/yugoslav-hist1.htm |archivedate=16 August 2013 |df= }} </ref>

The Republic of Croatia, by an act of the [[Croatian Parliament]] in 1995, started to officially commemorate the victims at Bleiburg,<ref name="Vukusic">{{cite book|last=Vukušić|first=Božo|title=Bleiburg Memento|language=Croatian|publisher=Udruga Hrvatski Križni Put|location=Zagreb|year=2005|isbn=953-95007-0-2}}</ref> at a time when [[Franjo Tuđman]] and the [[Croatian Democratic Union]] (HDZ) were in power.

More recently, as commemorative events became less of a political event, the radicals were largely marginalized and the focus of the commemoration turned to the actual victims of the repatriations.<ref name="Pauković-2012"/> Many top-ranking politicians and Catholic and Muslim clerics visit the Bleiburg site annually. Prime Minister [[Ivica Račan]] visited the site in 2002.<ref>[http://www.vjesnik.hr/Html/2002/05/15/Clanak.asp?r=unu&c=1 Račan apologizes to those who suffered because of Bleiburg] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030916132203/http://www.vjesnik.hr/Html/2002/05/15/Clanak.asp?r=unu&c=1|date=16 September 2003}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Ivo Sanader]] visited the site in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vijesti.hrt.hr/arhiv/2004/02/20/HRT0021.html |title=PREMIJER IVO SANADER POSJETIO GRADIŠĆE I BLEIBURŠKO POLJE |accessdate=17 March 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402104539/http://vijesti.hrt.hr/arhiv/2004/02/20/HRT0021.html |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df= }}</ref> 

For the 60th anniversary commemorations in 2005 a large crowd was in attendance, with speeches by Croatian parliamentary speaker [[Vladimir Šeks]] and head of the Muslim Community of Croatia, Mufti [[Ševko Omerbašić]].<ref>[http://www.matis.hr/vijesti.php?id=96 60th anniversary of Bleiburg commemorated] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216233054/http://www.matis.hr/vijesti.php?id=96 |date=16 February 2008 }}</ref> In 2007, a new altar was installed at the site and was inaugurated by Cardinal [[Josip Bozanić]] before some 10,000 people.<ref>[http://www.jutarnji.hr/dogadjaji_dana/clanak/art-2007,5,8,zagreb_bleiburg,73533.jl Bozanić's mass at Bleiburg with record number of pilgrims], jutarnji.hr; accessed 24 March 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.javno.com/hr/hrvatska/clanak.php?id=43638 |title=Bozani: Komunizam je sustavno provodio zloine |publisher=javno.com |accessdate=17 March 2015 |language=Croatian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421113500/http://www.javno.com/hr/hrvatska/clanak.php?id=43638 |archivedate=21 April 2008 |df= }}</ref>

In 2007, Slovenia's government announced plans to make the [[Tezno trench]] a memorial park and cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarajevo-x.com/clanak/070906130|title=Mjesto ubijenih Hrvata iz Bleiburga kao memorijalni park|work=Klix.ba|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> In 2008, the Croatian and Slovenian governments reached an agreement of cooperation on organizing military cemeteries, similar to earlier agreements which Slovenia reached with Italy and Germany.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/7124/Default.aspx|newspaper=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|language=Croatian|title=Hrvatska i Slovenija se obavezale na dostojno obilježavanje masovnih grobnica|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref>

Croatia's [[Prime Minister of Croatia|Prime Minister]], [[Zoran Milanović]], visited Bleiburg in September 2008. He stated that all victims had the right to a fair trial, {{clarify|date=April 2015}} and that his motive was not political.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/milanovic-posjetio-bleiburg-motiv-odlaska-nije-bio-trgovacke-prirode/402048.aspx|title=Milanović posjetio Bleiburg: Motiv odlaska nije bio trgovačke prirode|publisher=index.hr|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>

In 2009, [[Croatian President]] [[Stjepan Mesić]] criticized the Parliament's representatives who did not react to people in the crowd displaying Ustaše iconography, which is ostensibly illegal in Croatia, at a state-sponsored event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oslobodjenje.ba/index.php?id=11749|newspaper=[[Oslobođenje]]|agency=[[HINA]]|language=Croatian|title=Mesić: Od Bleiburga ste napravili ustaški dernek|date=19 May 2009|accessdate=31 May 2012}}</ref> 

In 2010, Croatian president [[Ivo Josipović]] said he would not attend the year's May Bleiburg commemoration as long as Ustaše iconography was present,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/ivo-josipovic--u-bleiburg-necu-ici-dokle-god-se-tamo-pojavljuju-ljudi-u-crnom/483078|language=Croatian|title=Ivo Josipović: U Bleiburg neću ići dokle god se tamo pojavljuju ljudi u crnom|newspaper=Jutarnji list|date=12 January 2010|accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> although he did make a separate visit to the Bleiburg memorial in June in addition to his visit to the Tezno memorial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rtl.hr/vijesti/novosti/19617/josipovic-odao-pocast-zrtvama-na-bleiburgu|publisher=[[RTL Televizija]]|language=Croatian|title=Josipović odao počast žrtvama na Bleiburgu|date=20 June 2010|accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref>

In 2012, Croatia's parliament decided to revoke funding for the annual Bleiburg commemoration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://daily.tportal.hr/188503/Bleiburg-commemoration-no-longer-to-be-held-under-parliament-s-auspices.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707132756/http://daily.tportal.hr/188503/Bleiburg-commemoration-no-longer-to-be-held-under-parliament-s-auspices.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=7 July 2012 |publisher=T-portal.hr |title=Bleiburg commemoration no longer to be held under parliament's auspices |date=17 April 2012 |accessdate=28 May 2012 }}</ref> The reason given by Milanović was that the government would not fund what had become a politically partisan event concentrating on the NDH, rather than mourning the victims.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seebiz.eu/milanovic-u-bleiburgu-se-komemorirala-vojska-ndh-a-ne-zrtve/ar-34698|newspaper=[[Southeast European Times]]|language=Croatian|title=Milanović: U Bleiburgu se komemorirala vojska NDH, a ne žrtve|date=12 May 2012|accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> In 2012, the Croatian leadership laid wreaths only at the monument in Tezno.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://daily.tportal.hr/193829/Top-Croatian-officials-commemorate-Tezno-victims.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709215210/http://daily.tportal.hr/193829/Top-Croatian-officials-commemorate-Tezno-victims.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=9 July 2012 |publisher=T-portal.hr |title=Top Croatian officials commemorate Tezno victims |date=15 May 2012 |accessdate=28 May 2012 }}</ref>

As Croatian academician Vjeran Pavlaković, an assistant professor in the Department of Cultural Studies at the [[University of Rijeka]], writes in ''Deifying the Defeated Commemorating Bleiburg since 1990'',<blockquote>''"The blurring of the past and the present is an integral part of the Bleiburg commemorations; not only do the participants dress in Ustasa uniforms, display Ustasa insignia and iconography, and sell paraphernalia associated with the NDH and its leaders, but there is an active discourse about the Croatian War of Independence accompanied by images of heroes (as well as individuals guilty of war crimes) from the conflict in the 1990s."''</blockquote> 
Pavlaković concludes that <blockquote>''"[T]he effectiveness of Bleiburg to act as a site of memory can be attributed to the fact that it represents both a traumatic past, as well as a moment of rupture, or historical discontinuity. Both of these factors give the commemorations at Bleiburg emotional weight and political significance, especially at a point when Croatia was going through another historical transition in the 1990s. It also meant that the Bleiburg myth was easily manipulated; the victims of the Bleiburg tragedy were actively invoked not only to distort the Ustasa past, but to justify the resurgence of extreme nationalist political options. The Bleiburg myth became one of many historical moments that symbolized Croatian martyrdom, due to the prevailing narrative of victimization by Greater Serbian aggression during the 1990s. The martyrium myth is one of the most common archetypes in the taxonomy of myths... The danger of presenting the victims of Bleiburg exclusively as martyrs for the Croatian state, however, is that the reality of the NDH regime and the crimes it committed are ignored in the new, revised narrative of World War Two.<ref>[https://www.cairn.info/revue-l-europe-en-formation-2010-3-page-125.htm#no7 ''Deifying the Defeated Commemorating Bleiburg since 1990''], cairn.info; accessed 11 March 2017.</ref></blockquote>

===Historiography===
Unlike many other operations of the Partisans, which have been described in detail, little has been written on operations in Slovenia near the Austrian border during the week of 7–15 May 1945.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=765}} Postwar Yugoslav literature ascribed all human losses in May and June 1945 as military casualties in the final operations of the war.{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=100}} All opposing armies and political opponents were characterized by the Yugoslav historiography as traitors and collaborators.{{sfn|Portmann|2004|p=46}} The events at Bleiburg were known as "final encirclement battles", "final military operations", and the "grand finale in Carinthia".{{sfn|Rulitz|2015|p=167}} Bleiburg repatriations and its aftermath were first discussed in emigrant literature by anti-communists that managed to leave the country. One of the first book dealing with the subject was ''La Tragedia de Bleiburg'', published by [[Croatian Argentines|Croatian emigrants]] in [[Buenos Aires]] in 1963.{{sfn|Grahek Ravančić|2009|p=13}}

''[[The Minister and the Massacres]]'', a 1986 book by [[Nikolai Tolstoy]],<ref name="Tolstoy-1986">[[#Tolstoy-1986|Tolstoy, 1986]]</ref> further publicized the issue, but it made various dubious claims about the repatriations that were roundly criticized by various historians and authors,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Horne|first=Alistair|title=The unquiet graves of Yalta.|journal=National Review|date=5 February 1990|volume=42|page=27|issn=0028-0038}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Pavlowitch|first=Stevan K.|title=The Minister and the Massacres review|journal=The English Historical Review|date=January 1989|volume=104|issue=410|pages=274–276|doi=10.1093/ehr/civ.ccccx.274}}</ref>{{sfn|Booker|1997|p=85}}{{sfn|Booker|1997|p=188}} although it brought attention, more generally, to the persistent distortion of the story,{{sfn|Booker|1997|p=85}} and to the issue of historians trusting contemporary records and purported eyewitness.<ref>[[#Musgrove-2009|Musgrove (Ed.) 2009]], p. 70</ref><ref>[[#Rees-2007|Rees, 2007]].</ref>

Croatian-American historian Jozo Tomasevich described the events: "The annihilation of most quisling troops captured at the end of the war – which is a fact – was an act of mass terror and brutal political surgery, similar to that practiced by the Ustašas and the Chetniks earlier in the war."{{sfn|Portmann|2004|p=70}} Regarding Partisan treatment of Ustaše prisoners, Tomasevich notes: "Considering the nature of the struggle among the various competing forces during the Second World War in Yugoslavia, atrocities against the Serbian population in the territory of the Independent State of Croatia and pro-Partisan or dissident Croats, the fact that the Ustaše adhered to the Nazis to the bitter end, and finally the fact that the Ustaša leadership wanted to put its troops at the disposal of the Western Allies for possible use against Yugoslav and other Communists, no mercy on the part of the Yugoslav Partisans toward these troops could have been expected."<ref name="Tomasevich 1969 pp.113-114">[[#Tomasevich_1969|Tomasevich (1969)]], pp. 113–14</ref>

British political scientist [[David Bruce MacDonald]] criticized the exaggeration of the number of victims:<ref name="MacDonald pp. 170-171">[[#MacDonald-2003|MacDonald, 2003]], pp.&nbsp;170–71</ref> "Inflating the numbers of dead at Bleiburg had several layers of significance. Firstly, it gave the Croats their own massacre at the hands of Serbs and/or Communists, which allowed them to counter the Serbs' Jasenovac genocide with one of their own. Secondly, it allowed Croats to distance themselves from the Serbs and the Communist regime that had carried out the massacres. They could portray Croatia as an unwilling participant in the SFRY, more a prisoner than a constituent nation. Thirdly, by suffering such a massacre, the Croats underwent their own 'way of Cross', as dubbed by most Croatians."

Regarding Tito's responsibility for the actions of the Partisans at the end of the war, Croatian lawyer Dominik Vuletić wrote: "...it should be mentioned that at the time of the Bleiburg events and the death marches that followed, he was the Prime Minister (DFJ), [[Ministry of Defence (Yugoslavia)|Minister of Defence]], General Secretary of the Communist Party and the Supreme Commander of all Yugoslav Armed Forces, so de facto and de iure he had control over all the forces and was the most responsible individual in the country. The Yugoslav forces that participated in the Bleiburg events acted according to Tito's instructions and were under his control. [...] So, there can be no doubt that Josip Broz Tito had full effective control over the units involved in the crimes."{{sfn|Vuletić|2007|p=137}} On 13 May, Tito allegedly dispatched a handwritten telegram to the supreme headquarters of the Slovene Partisan Army that arrived on 14 May, prohibiting "in the sternest language" the execution of prisoners of war and commanding the transfer of possible suspects to a military court. The authenticity of this telegram is disputed as it was not published in any collection of documents of the Yugoslav Army and did not have Tito's signature. Historian Nikolai Tolstoy called it "a clear forgery".{{sfn|Grahek Ravančić|2009|pp=139-143}}

British historian [[Keith Lowe (author)|Keith Lowe]] dealt with the end of the war in his book ''Savage Continent: Europe in the Aftermath of World War II'', where he wrote: "For countless millions of people throughout the eastern half of the continent, therefore, the end of the war did not signal ‘liberation’ at all, it merely heralded a new era of state repression. The Nazi terror was over: the Communist terror was about to begin".{{sfn|Lowe|2012|p=265}}

===In popular culture===
The surrender at Bleiburg was the subject of a 1999 film, ''[[Četverored]]'', based on the 1997 novel of the same name by [[Ivan Aralica]]. Croatian-Australian painter [[Charles Billich]] painted a series of works on the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.croatianhistory.net/etf/art.html|title=Croatian art|author=Darko Zubrinic|publisher=croatianhistory.net|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>

