{{Use British English|date=December 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}} {{Infobox organization | name = Guild of St Matthew | named_after = [[Matthew the Apostle]] | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | logo = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | abbreviation = | motto = | merged = | successor = | formation = 29 June 1877 | founder = [[Stewart Headlam]] | founding_location = [[Bethnal Green]], England | dissolved = 1909 | merger = | type = | status = | purpose = | headquarters = | location = | coords = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} --> | region = | services = | methods = | fields = | membership = | membership_year = | leader_title = Warden | leader_name = Stewart Headlam | key_people = | main_organ = | parent_organization = | subsidiaries = | secessions = | affiliations = | budget = | budget_year = | revenue = | revenue_year = | disbursements = | expenses = | expenses_year = | endowment = | endowment_year = | staff = | staff_year = | volunteers = | volunteers_year = | slogan = | mission = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | remarks = | formerly = | footnotes = }} The '''Guild of St Matthew''' was an English [[high church|high-church]] [[Christian socialism|Christian socialist]] association led by [[Stewart Headlam]] from its establishment in [[Bethnal Green]] on 29 June 1877 to its dissolution in 1909.{{sfnm |1a1=Jones |1y=1968 |1p=102 |2a1=Leighton |2y=2004 |2p=230 |3a1=Marsden |3y=1998 |3pp=196–197}} While the guild never had a membership of more than about 400 people, it was "the pioneer Christian socialist society of the revival period in Britain", breaking the ground for other Christian socialist organisations yet to come, such as the [[Christian Social Union (UK)|Christian Social Union]].{{sfnm |1a1=Jones |1y=1968 |1p=99 |2a1=Leech |2y=1989 |2p=3}} [[Kenneth Leech]] described it as "the first explicitly [[socialist]] group in Britain".{{sfn|Leech|1989|p=3}} For many years, it published the periodical ''The Church Reformer''. __